Three other recordings of the same Arctic Warbler are at XC279149, XC279150 and XC279152. This recording is different because of the heavy rain falling in the background. The rain had just started. In fact, it lasted for an amazing 24 hours and caused considerable flooding in nearby areas of the Irish mainland. The Arctic Warbler was in a sycamore tree whose remaining foliage was barely able to provide shelter, although the bird was feeding well on insects among withered leaves and twigs. Shortly after it flew off, presumably to find better shelter. Next day it was much more quiet and scarcely called, despite being watched for long periods (or rather, the habitat that concealed it was watched). The call is sharp and sudden and beats like a somewhat erratic pulse: sometimes repeated at the same interval, sometimes not; sometimes louder and piqued, sometimes sotto voce, although always piercing.

The second note overlapped with Hypsipetes amaurotis and
there was no information about the power below 5 kHz.
I found the bird after listening the calls and captured photos and videos,
but the ID was difficult from the appearance.

rmk:
A recording of the contact call of an Arctic Warbler _Phylloscopus borealis_. This is the first confirmed Arctic Warbler detected on Christmas Island, Australia, although it has been detected before on Cocos (Keeling) Islands and Ashmore Reef.
The Arctic Warbler is calling regularly at roughly 1.2 second intervals throughout the recording but is not very loud compared with other species calling and environmental noise.
The recording has not been filtered but has been clipped from the original recording and amplified to this level.
